NAME: Keystone XL
properties.text2: STATUS: Keystone XL is phase IV of the Keystone System, which is intended to bring heavy crude from the Oil Sands region in Alberta to the Patoka and Cushing terminals, and then on to the refineries and export terminals of the Gulf Coast. In February of 2015 President Obama vetoed US legislation to permit construction of the pipeline, but his action was reversed by President Trump in 2017. After other legal challenges, on March 31, 2020, TC Energy announced it would commence work on the project. However, as reported by E&E News, on April 15, 2020, a US District judge revoked the project's water-crossing permit, requiring the US Army Corps of Engineers to suspend any dredge or fill activities at water crossings.

NAME: Trans Mountain Expansion
properties.image: OWNER: Canada Development Investment Corporation (purchased from Kinder Morgan in August 2018 for C$4.5 billion after long-term resistance from indigenous peoples, environmentalists and more recently, the provincial government of British Columbia)
properties.text2: STATUS: The expansion project adds a new pipeline roughly parrallel to the existing route. It would be used for diluted bitumen (dilbit), increasing the system's capacity from 300,000 to 890,000 barrels a day; the dilbit would be loaded into tankers headed through the Strait of San Juan de Fuca on their way to the open sea. After the government's purchase of the project, a federal court ruled that it had not sufficiently consulted with First Nations or performed an adequate environmental review of the increased tanker traffic. However, on February 4, 2020, as reported by NPR, the same Federal Court of Appeal ruled against four First Nations, finding that the consultation process had now been adequately performed and refusing to hear other charges concerning environmental risks. In the meantime, as reported by Reuters, the anticipated costs of the project has risen from C$7.4 billion to C$12.6 billion.

NAME: Line 3 Existing Pipeline
properties.text2: STATUS: As stated on the Stop Line 3 website: "The existing Line 3 is an Enbridge pipeline that ships crude oil from Alberta to Superior, Wisconsin. It spans northern Minnesota, crossing the Leech Lake and Fond du Lac reservations and the 1855, 1854, and 1842 treaty areas. And it is a ticking time bomb. It was built with defective steel in l961, has had numerous ruptures and spills, and is running at half pressure because of severe corrosion. Instead of cleaning up this liability, Enbridge wants to simply abandon it in the ground forever, and cut a brand new energy corridor through our best lakes, wetlands, and wild rice beds, and the heart of Ojibwe treaty territory." (source)

NAME: Line 3 Replacement
properties.text2: STATUS: As stated on the Stop Line 3 website: "At $7.5 billion, the proposed new Line 3 would be the largest project in Enbridges history and one of the largest crude oil pipelines in the world, carrying up to 915,000 barrels per day of one of the dirtiest fuel on earth, tar sands crude. They call it a 'replacement' but it is larger, with higher volume, in a new corridor. First Nations, tribal governments, landowners, environmental groups, and communities across the Great Lakes have been fighting for 5 years now to stop this new corridor and #StopLine3. We are here to protect the water and our future generations." (source)

NAME: Dakota Access Pipeline (DAPL)
properties.image: OWNERS: Energy Transfer Partners, Phillips 66, affiliates of Enbridge and of Marathon Petroleum
properties.text2: STATUS: After many months of native-led protest at Standing Rock in 2016, the 1,172-mile-long pipeline was authorized by the incoming Trump administration and currently delivers over half a million barrels of crude oil per day to the Patoka Terminal in Illinois. But on March 25, 2020, as reported in the New York Times, the Standing Rock Sioux Tribe won a suit in a federal court against the Army Corps of Engineers for failure to conduct an adequate environmental review. The next step will be a decision as to whether the oil can continue flowing while a full review is carried out under the provisions of the National Environmental Policy Act.
